01:11:13,643 --> 01:11:17,343
They just stood there, confused.
They wouldn't run.

713
01:11:17,480 --> 01:11:20,516
But you could - and you did, didn't you?

714
01:11:20,650 --> 01:11:24,349
Yes. I took one lamb
and I ran away as fast as I could.

715
01:11:24,486 --> 01:11:28,780
- Where were you going, Clarice?
- I don't know. I didn't have any food,

716
01:11:28,907 --> 01:11:32,191
any water and it was very cold, very cold.

717
01:11:34,369 --> 01:11:36,362
I thought...

718
01:11:36,497 --> 01:11:39,581
I thought if I could save just one, but...

719
01:11:41,001 --> 01:11:43,574
He was so heavy.

720
01:11:43,712 --> 01:11:45,752
So heavy.

721
01:11:50,551 --> 01:11:55,343
I didn't get more than a few miles
when the sheriff's car picked me up.

722
01:11:57,683 --> 01:12:02,559
The rancher was so angry, he sent me
to live at the orphanage in Bozeman.

723
01:12:02,688 --> 01:12:04,929
I never saw the ranch again.

724
01:12:05,398 --> 01:12:08,103
What became of your lamb, Clarice?

725
01:12:10,111 --> 01:12:13,894
- He killed him.
- You still wake up sometimes, don't you?

726
01:12:14,031 --> 01:12:16,522
Wake up in the dark

727
01:12:16,658 --> 01:12:19,409
and hear the screaming of the lambs?

728
01:12:19,994 --> 01:12:22,032
Yes.

729
01:12:22,704 --> 01:12:26,915
And you think, if you save poor Catherine,
you could make them stop, don't you?

730
01:12:27,041 --> 01:12:29,200
You think if Catherine lives,

731
01:12:29,335 --> 01:12:32,716
you won't wake up in the dark ever again

732
01:12:32,851 --> 01:12:35,686
to that awful screaming of the lambs.

733
01:12:36,855 --> 01:12:38,265
I don't know.

734
01:12:38,939 --> 01:12:40,813
I don't know.

735
01:12:41,942 --> 01:12:43,982
Thank you, Clarice.

736
01:12:44,820 --> 01:12:49,114
- Thank you.
- Tell me his name, Doctor.

737
01:12:55,246 --> 01:12:58,033
Dr Chilton, I presume.

738
01:12:58,165 --> 01:13:00,621
I think you know each other.

739
01:13:02,086 --> 01:13:04,126
OK.

740
01:13:04,922 --> 01:13:08,457
- Let's go.
- It's your turn, Doctor.

741
01:13:08,592 --> 01:13:10,668
- Out.
- Tell me his name.

742
01:13:10,802 --> 01:13:14,930
Sorry, ma'am. I've got orders. I have
to put you on a plane. Come on now.

743
01:13:15,056 --> 01:13:17,345
Brave Clarice.

744
01:13:17,475 --> 01:13:21,058
You will let me know when those lambs
stop screaming, won't you?

745
01:13:21,187 --> 01:13:25,730
- Tell me his name, Doctor.
- Clarice.

746
01:13:25,858 --> 01:13:28,561
Your case file.

747
01:13:32,738 --> 01:13:35,490
Goodbye, Clarice.

748
01:14:40,227 --> 01:14:44,272
- Ready when you are, doc.
- Just another minute, please.

749
01:14:53,406 --> 01:14:57,949
Son of a bitch demanded a second
dinner. Lamb chops, extra rare.

750
01:14:58,077 --> 01:15:02,904
I wonder what he wants for breakfast.
Some damn thing from the zoo?

751
01:15:24,143 --> 01:15:27,890
- Good evening, gentlemen.
- OK, doc. Grab some floor.

752
01:15:28,021 --> 01:15:30,060
Same drill as before, please.

753
01:15:36,904 --> 01:15:39,691
Ready when you are, Sergeant Pembry.

754
01:15:55,724 --> 01:15:57,763
OK.

755
01:16:03,731 --> 01:16:05,770
Hand me that, would ya?

756
01:16:11,071 --> 01:16:13,111
Thanks.

757
01:16:16,076 --> 01:16:18,862
Mind the drawings, please.

758
01:16:21,080 --> 01:16:23,119
Thank you.

759
01:16:46,770 --> 01:16:49,475
Watch it. He's cuffed me!

760
01:16:56,028 --> 01:16:58,068
Jesus Christ!

761
01:18:16,320 --> 01:18:19,107
Ready when you are, Sergeant Pembry.

762
01:18:28,248 --> 01:18:30,324
What is this shit?

763
01:18:32,626 --> 01:18:36,458
- Did somebody go up on five?
- No. Nobody went up.

764
01:18:36,589 --> 01:18:39,708
Call Pembry. Ask him to tell...

765
01:18:41,218 --> 01:18:45,382
CP. Shots fired on five.
Repeat: Shots fired on five.

766
01:18:45,514 --> 01:18:47,554
Sergeant Tate.

767
01:18:49,642 --> 01:18:52,264
- Holy shit.
- What the hell...?

768
01:18:53,521 --> 01:18:56,094
Shut up. Bobby, get the vest.

769
01:18:56,232 --> 01:18:59,067
- Right, sarge.
- Brady, Howard, cover...

770
01:18:59,193 --> 01:19:01,232
Look!

771
01:19:03,196 --> 01:19:07,656
- It's stopped.
- Seal off a ten-block radius.

772
01:19:07,783 --> 01:19:10,547
Get me the SWAT team
and an ambulance double-quick.

773
01:19:10,673 --> 01:19:12,630
We're goin' up.

774
01:19:41,076 --> 01:19:43,152
Pembry!

775
01:19:44,121 --> 01:19:46,160
Boyle!

776
01:19:58,592 --> 01:20:00,834
Oh, God.

777
01:20:07,016 --> 01:20:09,056
Go.

778
01:20:16,024 --> 01:20:19,144
- Clear.
- Command post.

779
01:20:19,277 --> 01:20:21,732
Two officers down.

780
01:20:23,072 --> 01:20:26,275
- Lecter's gone, sarge.
- Prisoner is missing.

781
01:20:26,408 --> 01:20:30,868
- Boyle's gun is gone, Sergeant.
- Repeat: Lecter is missing and armed.

782
01:20:30,995 --> 01:20:35,372
He's stripped the bed. Might be
makin' a rope. Check all windows.

783
01:20:35,917 --> 01:20:38,407
Where the fuck is my ambulance?

784
01:20:39,044 --> 01:20:43,255
He's alive. Sergeant Tate, he's alive.

785
01:20:43,590 --> 01:20:47,172
Get a hold of him
and feel his hand. Talk to him.

786
01:20:47,301 --> 01:20:51,097
- What do I say?
- It's Jim Pembry. Talk to him, dammit!

787
01:20:52,443 --> 01:20:54,566
Lecter is missing and armed.

788
01:20:54,695 --> 01:20:56,902
Pembry, can you hear me?

789
01:20:57,031 --> 01:21:01,942
He took Boyle's gun. Pembry got off one
round. There's a chance Lecter was hit.

790
01:21:02,078 --> 01:21:05,908
Keep breathin' in and out.
That's it. You're doing a good job.

791
01:21:06,039 --> 01:21:08,411
You look real good.

792
01:21:08,541 --> 01:21:11,412
Yeah, you look real good.

793
01:21:28,392 --> 01:21:30,266
- You ready?
- Let's do it.

794
01:21:30,394 --> 01:21:32,434
Let's go.

795
01:21:42,739 --> 01:21:46,902
Looking good, Pembry. You're gonna
make it. You're doin' just fine.

796
01:21:47,035 --> 01:21:49,442
I need that IV now!

797
01:21:49,579 --> 01:21:53,658
Can we get the straps?
Where's the fucking oxygen?

798
01:21:53,790 --> 01:21:56,246
Stay with me. Stay with me here.

799
01:21:57,294 --> 01:21:59,749
We're losin' him. Downstairs.

800
01:22:00,380 --> 01:22:02,953
And up.

801
01:22:03,091 --> 01:22:05,131
Elevator!

802
01:22:10,723 --> 01:22:12,549
CP to Tate.

803
01:22:12,683 --> 01:22:15,553
Roger, Lieutenant. Tate here.

804
01:22:15,686 --> 01:22:18,640
I'm on the elevator
bringing Pembry down.

805
01:22:18,772 --> 01:22:21,262
He seems to be hangin' on.

806
01:22:21,399 --> 01:22:23,890
Top three floors secured.

807
01:22:24,026 --> 01:22:26,066
Main stairwell secured.

808
01:22:27,112 --> 01:22:29,151
We think he's on two.

809
01:22:42,179 --> 01:22:44,634
Tate, are you still with me?

810
01:22:46,266 --> 01:22:51,508
We're pretty sure he's somewhere on two,
sir. That's all for now. Over.

811
01:23:10,205 --> 01:23:12,660
He's on the roof of the elevator.

812
01:23:15,293 --> 01:23:17,286
OK, guys.

813
01:23:33,391 --> 01:23:34,766
I see him.

814
01:23:34,892 --> 01:23:37,181
There's a gun by his hand.
He's not moving.

815
01:23:37,978 --> 01:23:40,813
- One warning: We need him alive.
- Got it.

816
01:23:41,857 --> 01:23:44,728
Lecter, put your hands on your head.

817
01:23:47,696 --> 01:23:49,736
One in the leg.

818
01:24:00,249 --> 01:24:02,408
No movement.

819
01:24:03,002 --> 01:24:06,122
Johnny, hold your fire.
We're comin' into the car.

820
01:24:06,255 --> 01:24:08,543
We're openin' the hatch.

821
01:24:08,673 --> 01:24:11,888
Watch his hands.
If there's any fire, it'll come from us.

822
01:24:12,022 --> 01:24:14,098
- Affirm.
- Got it.

823
01:24:40,214 --> 01:24:42,253
Memphis General, medical unit 26.

824
01:24:42,382 --> 01:24:46,795
We're inbound with a male police officer
with severe facial lacerations.

825
01:24:46,928 --> 01:24:51,554
Weapon unknown. We've got grand mal
seizure activity but he's post-ictal now.

826
01:24:51,682 --> 01:24:54,636
Vital signs are good.
Pressure is 130 over 90.

827
01:24:54,768 --> 01:24:57,176
- 90?
- Yeah, that's right, 90. Pulse 84.

828
01:24:57,313 --> 01:25:02,270
We got him on lactated Ringer's and
the patient is on ten litres of oxygen...

829
01:25:09,073 --> 01:25:14,530
They found the ambulance in a parking
garage at the airport. Crew was dead.

830
01:25:14,996 --> 01:25:18,743
He killed a tourist, too.
Got his clothes, cash.

831
01:25:19,165 --> 01:25:22,416
- By now he could be anywhere.
- He won't come after me.

832
01:25:22,544 --> 01:25:24,833
- Oh, really?
- He won't.

833
01:25:24,963 --> 01:25:29,506
I can't explain it.
He would consider that rude.

834
01:25:29,634 --> 01:25:33,500
- It's over. She's dead.
- It's not your fault it worked out like this.

835
01:25:33,637 --> 01:25:38,050
The thing is that Lecter said everything
we need to catch him is in these pages.

836
01:25:38,183 --> 01:25:40,673
Dr Lecter said a lot of things.

837
01:25:40,810 --> 01:25:43,265
He's here, Ardelia.

838
01:26:11,809 --> 01:26:14,264
Is this Lecter's handwriting?

839
01:26:15,645 --> 01:26:20,141
"Clarice, doesn't this random scattering
of sites seem desperately random,

840
01:26:20,274 --> 01:26:24,105
like the elaboration of a bad liar?
Hannibal Lecter."

841
01:26:24,236 --> 01:26:26,940
Desperately random?
What does he mean?

842
01:26:27,072 --> 01:26:31,568
Not random at all, maybe.
Like there's some pattern here.

843
01:26:31,701 --> 01:26:34,905
But there is no pattern
or the computers would have nailed it.

844
01:26:35,038 --> 01:26:39,664
- They were even found in random order.
- Random because of the one girl.

845
01:26:39,792 --> 01:26:43,789
- The one he weighted down.
- Fredrica Bimmel.

846
01:26:44,129 --> 01:26:47,295
From Belvedere, Ohio.

847
01:26:47,423 --> 01:26:50,377
First girl taken, third body found.

848
01:26:50,510 --> 01:26:53,427
- Why?
- She didn't drift. He weighted her down.

849
01:26:53,554 --> 01:26:56,922
What did Lecter say
about the first principles?

850
01:26:57,057 --> 01:27:02,217
- Simplicity.
- What does this guy do? He covets.

851
01:27:02,354 --> 01:27:04,892
How do we first start to covet?

852
01:27:05,272 --> 01:27:08,688
- We covet what we see...
- Every day.

853
01:27:10,611 --> 01:27:13,895
- Hot damn, Clarice.
- He knew her.

854
01:27:18,576 --> 01:27:22,276
BELVEDERE, OHIO

855
01:28:29,027 --> 01:28:31,067
- Mr Bimmel?
- That's me.

856
01:28:32,239 --> 01:28:34,812
I'm Clarice Starling. I'm with the FBI.

857
01:28:38,744 --> 01:28:42,327
I sure appreciate you letting me
take a look around, Mr Bimmel.

858
01:28:42,456 --> 01:28:44,698
I don't know nothin' new to tell ya.

859
01:28:44,834 --> 01:28:48,250
Police been back here
so many times already.

860
01:28:48,379 --> 01:28:52,542
Fredrica went into Chicago
on the bus to see about a job.

861
01:28:52,675 --> 01:28:56,208
She left the interview OK.
She never come home.

862
01:28:59,097 --> 01:29:01,503
Her bedroom's how she left it.

863
01:29:01,640 --> 01:29:04,260
Upstairs. Door to the left.

864
01:31:50,023 --> 01:31:53,474
He's making himself a "woman suit",
Mr Crawford, out of real women.

865
01:31:53,609 --> 01:31:56,147
He can sew, this guy. He's very skilled.

866
01:31:56,279 --> 01:31:58,651
- He's a tailor or a dressmaker.
- Starling...

867
01:31:58,781 --> 01:32:02,398
That's why they're so big. He has to
keep them alive so he can starve them,

868
01:32:02,534 --> 01:32:06,199
- so that he can loosen their skin.
- Starling, we know who he is.

869
01:32:06,329 --> 01:32:08,405
And where he is.
We're on our way right now.

870
01:32:08,540 --> 01:32:11,494
- Where?
- Calumet City, edge of Chicago.

871
01:32:11,626 --> 01:32:14,378
Be on the ground in 45 minutes.

872
01:32:14,504 --> 01:32:16,710
That's great news, sir, but how...

873
01:32:16,839 --> 01:32:20,421
Johns Hopkins came up with some
names. We fed 'em into Known Offenders.

874
01:32:20,550 --> 01:32:24,630
Subject's name
is Jamie Gumb, a.k. A John Grant.

875
01:32:24,929 --> 01:32:28,464
Lecter's description was accurate.
He just lied about the name.

876
01:32:28,599 --> 01:32:30,853
Customs had some paper on him.

877
01:32:30,988 --> 01:32:36,527
They stopped a carton two years ago
at LAX. Live caterpillars from Surinam.

878
01:32:36,660 --> 01:32:39,577
The addressee was a Jame Gumb.

879
01:32:40,163 --> 01:32:43,034
Chicago's only 400 miles from here.
I'll be there in...

880
01:32:43,166 --> 01:32:47,579
No, Starling. There's not enough time.
We want him for murder, not kidnapping.

881
01:32:47,712 --> 01:32:51,756
I need you to link him to the Bimmel girl.
See what you can dredge up in Belvedere.

882
01:32:51,882 --> 01:32:54,088
Yes, sir, you bet. I'll do my best.

883
01:32:54,218 --> 01:32:57,883
Starling, we wouldn't
have found him without you.

884
01:32:58,013 --> 01:33:01,512
Nobody's gonna forget that.
Least of all me.

885
01:33:02,893 --> 01:33:06,641
Thank you, sir.
Thank you very much, Mr Crawford.

886
01:33:07,897 --> 01:33:09,308
Mr Crawford?

887
01:33:21,869 --> 01:33:24,324
Thanks for the scraps, asshole.

888
01:33:24,454 --> 01:33:26,909
I got a better idea.

889
01:33:47,767 --> 01:33:50,636
OK, Precious. Time for a little treat.

890
01:34:03,322 --> 01:34:05,361
Precious!

891
01:34:07,200 --> 01:34:09,824
Come on, girl!

892
01:34:09,958 --> 01:34:12,456
Come on, Precious.

